<TEXT>
students at two california high schools gahr and 
nearby cerritos took a current events quiz last week and the 
results could help decide whether commercial television gets a place 
in the classroom 
the quizzes were part of a research effort designed to see if a 
daily tv news show that includes paid advertising is helping 
students learn 
the nearly 2000 students at gahr high school in cerritos 
calif have been able to watch the news show called channel one for 
the past two weeks on 91 new television sets given to the school and 
installed in every classroom 
the youngsters at cerritos high school whose enrollment numbers 
and characteristics resemble those of its suburban los angeles 
neighbor havent had a chance to see the news show but agreed to 
take the quiz anyway 
whittle communications lp the knoxville tennbased media 
concern that developed channel one plans to tally the results from 
these schools along with those from tests at the five other schools 
in the channel one project and their sister schools and see if the 
show is helping educate students 
backers of the program are betting that the research will show a 
significant difference in the results from the schools that have 
been exposed to the show and those that have not 
that could be a critical element in whittles efforts to persuade 
other schools to sign up for the channel one project whittle hopes 
to expand the service to as many as 8000 schools nationwide in the 
fall of 1990 
we expect to see real differences and if we do it will be a 
real plus for the program whittle chairman christopher whittle 
said friday in a telelphone interview 
the main obstacle to the project appears to be the intense 
opposition from childrens advocates and some education groups who 
say companies should not be allowed to pitch their products to an 
essentially captive audience in school 
groups such as the national association of secondary school 
principals and the national parentteacher association have opposed 
it 
peggy charren head of action for childrens television a 
massachusettsbased childrens advocacy group said she thinks the 
channel one test has been orchestrated to gloss over the bad 
precedent she says is being set of allowing commercials in 
classrooms 
the problem is we are selling children to advertisers they 
think they are going to get enough kids buying enough products to 
make the investment worthwhile mrs charren said 
the test of channel one began march 6 at gahr and five others 
schools mumford high school in detroit withrow high school in 
cincinnati eisenhower middle school in kansas city kan billerica 
memorial high school near boston and central high school in 
knoxville 
each school was given about 50000 in televisions video 
recorders and a satellite dish to recieve a daily 12minute news 
show with up to two minutes of paid ads the sponsors include levis 
jeans snickers candy bars and clearasil acne cream 
in return the schools are asked to play the show once each 
school day 
the test is to include five weeks of programs over a sevenweek 
period channel one has just begun a twoweek hiatus for spring 
break during which the producers hope to finetune the program 
a typical news show relates the days top stories and contains 
features on subjects like the environment and the lifetsyles of 
soviet teenagers 
last week channel one also carried a live 15minute special 
without commercials on the launch of the space shuttle discovery 
to test if the show is effective whittle plans to give quizzes 
at all six schools and their sister schools in each district for 
comparison 
students at gahr and cerritos got 29 multiple choice questions 
most of which came from information in the past weeks shows 
whittle said his company is also conducting two other types of 
studies to measure the effectiveness of the project 
he said one involves group interviews with teachers or students 
from the schools the other involves telephone interviews with 
students who have gotten their parents permission to talk about the 
commercials on the program 
whittle said the comparative quiz results the group discussions 
and the telephone polling will all figure in whether his company 
invests more than 100 million in hardware alone that he said will 
be required to go national 
five weeks isnt a very long time but we ought to be able to 
show some movement he said 
</TEXT>
