<TEXT>
leaders of the futures industry returned home from 
their annual convention in florida with sunburns and a stinging 
admonition from some concerned congressmen to clean up their 
business 
about two dozen federal lawmakers spoke during last weeks 
fourday meeting of the futures industry association and their 
message to the approximately 1000 brokers and exchange officials 
was clear put your house in order because congress is coming 
through 
it is incumbent upon you to open your eyes to wrongdoing where 
it exists and be assertive and effective in rooting it out even at 
the expense of making some internal fundamental changes to try to 
do it yourself rather than waiting for someone else to do it to 
you said rep dan glickman dkan during a panel discussion on 
saturday 
the futures industry is due for an official review as part of the 
congressional process for reauthorizing the commodity futures 
trading commission the federal agency that regulates futures 
trading the cftcs current 3year authorization expires on sept 30 
the recent disclosure of a sweeping justice department 
investigation of suspected trading fraud at chicagos two 
worldleading futures exchanges has heightened public interest in 
the industry and brought demands for intense scrutiny and reform of 
these onceobscure markets 
out there in the country our constituents dont know a lot 
about futures trading none of them have ever heard of the cftc it 
is important as we look at this industry that they know the 
importance of it said rep robin tallon dsc who sits on a 
house agriculture subcommittee that is conducting one of several 
congressional reviews of the industry 
a future is a binding contract to buy or sell a bundle of 
commodities or financial instruments at a specified price at a 
future date 
agricultural commodity futures have been traded at the chicago 
board of trade the worlds largest futures exchange for more than 
140 years but most of the action now is in financial futures which 
were invented in the 1970s and are heavily used by institutional 
investors around the world to reduce their risks in the 
international stock bond and currency markets 
the justice departments probe of suspected cheating by traders 
at the chicago board of trade and the chicago mercantile exchange 
has yielded no charges since it was revealed on jan 19 
nevertheless some key lawmakers who attended last weeks 
industry meeting in boca raton fla indicated support for 
beefing up cftcs tradesurveillance and ruleenforcement 
operations 
tightening up recordkeeping by futures exchanges and brokerage 
firms 
cracking down on certain trading practices that some believe 
provide opportunities to cheat 
if the futures industry cannot satisfactorily police itself 
several lawmakers implied it will lose its cherished freedom to set 
and enforce most of its own rules 
our committee is not going to resolve in favor of 
selfregulation unless there is a perception that it seems to be 
working universally said sen richard lugar of indiana the 
ranking republican member of the senate agriculture committee which 
also oversees futures regulation 
over and over during the florida meeting exchange officials 
vowed to improve their auditing of trades and to root out and punish 
wrongdoers 
certainly we can do better than we have done leo melamed 
chairman of the chicago mercs executive committee told lugar on 
saturday i give you the entire promise of my whole being that we 
will respond in every possible way that we can to your message 
rep david nagle diowa suggested that futures leaders view the 
various investigations of their industry as an opportunity to 
recapture the one commodity you can never afford to lose the 
universal recognition of the integrity of your markets 
